We pray and meditate, not as a way to escape, but as a way to tap into the vision, the purpose, and the power God has given us to bring more light, love, and freedom into this earth. 

On this Martin Luther King Jr. Day, celebrating my fellow Morehouse and Alpha Phi Alpha brother, I hope we all take intentional time to reflect on how engrained white supremacy is into the fabric and foundation of this country. And how much it would serve us all to self-educate and identify the ways in which we uphold that false ideology. Both through self-centered capitalistic ambition and in our gleeful march toward individualism with a glaring apathy for those around us. How we instinctively tear each other down while withholding deserved love, praise, and support from those who need it most. 

I’m praying we can reflect today on our inherent interconnectedness, and find actionable ways to empathetically and lovingly engage with our communities in hopes of closing the fabricated gaps, divisions, and stratifications the American white supremacist caste system has created. As individuals and as a collective we are called to be better. See you all tonight 🙏🏾

As an artist, producer, and songwriter, my main goals are to get better every day, and to create and share incredible music with incredible people. Working on @anusha.savi Marigold EP as producer, co- EP, and manager has been all of that and more. 

A year ago this week, @stargate put me in a room to work with emerging artists @anusha.savi and @lydiasamuel as a producer, songwriter, and recording engineer. We all wanted to make a pop record that captured their journeys as South Asian American women but, more importantly, we wanted to create something honest and meaningful that we all loved. We meditated, shared references from Bollywood, Tollywood, pop, and soul, and created Marigold with both artists delivering stunning vocal performances that would eventually win @laamp’s first Vocal Performance of the Year award. Not only was a powerful song born that week, but also a shared vision between @anushasavi and me about a sound and a project that we were both excited to pour ourselves into. One year later, as Anusha’s manager and co-executive producer, we’ve signed a deal with @outervoicerecords, released 4 singles - two of which are in rotation with @BBC radio via @urgirlpritt, played 11 shows from LA to NYC, and have reached tens of thousands of new fans with her music. And now, Anusha’s debut EP “Marigold” is finally out and we couldn’t be more proud to share this labor of love. 

Anusha is one of the hardest working people I’ve ever met. She is laser-focused on executing her vision while remaining humble enough to take feedback and even criticism as opportunities to grow. This isn’t your typical manager-artist relationship. We’re partners in this, and I’m grateful to be a part of the squad. With dozens of bangers already in the vault, this is only the beginning. It features a bonus version of Marigold with @lydiasamuel’s silky delivery and a reproduction by me and @imboybennett that sets the tone for more music to come. It’s only the beginning. Go follow @anusha.savi on all platforms to join the movement and to make sure you don’t miss this drop. Thank you all for your support.

I’m so damn proud of my wife. This  article and the work @elainewelteroth is doing right now leaves no room for doubt that the past 18 months of pregnancy and postpartum has been divinely orchestrated. Elaine has gracefully and vulnerably walked through physical pain, fear, disappointment, trauma, and countless life transitions, all to turn it into powerful advocacy for those who need it most. 

Her journalistic approach to her own birthing journey has become a much needed testimony amplifying the Black maternal mortality crisis caused by a deadly combination of racism, misogyny, and perverse incentives in our medical system. It should not be on the shoulders of mothers to fight for themselves when birthing trauma can be so layered and jarring that many women never revisit out of self preservation.

So all of us have to be aware and activated in the fight to keep Black mother’s alive. The least we can do is read Elaine’s article to get a sense for the reality of the crisis and what can be done to support organizations like @4kira4moms and @kindredspacela who are actively fighting for change. Please read the article, for Elaine, for all Black women, for mothers, and for all birthing people who deserve so much better. Article in her bio and in my stories.

#DigitalGirl is finally out! 

I remember the first song I ever wrote. I was 6 or 7, and my best friend and I both had a crush on a girl who didn’t like either of us. So we wrote a deeply immature song about how wrong this girl was for not seeing how cool we were. We weren’t cool, but like, we were 6 so what were we even taking about? 

Anyways, that song was poppy as hell, 6 year old funny, and somehow it initiated this theme of me writing songs about unrequited (imaginary) love. I been writing songs about heartbreak since before my heart was even fully formed and there’s just something super satisfying about upbeat sad songs. 

So in the spirit of The Killers - Mr. Brightside, Foster The People - Pumped Up Kicks, Kid Cudi - Pursuit of Happyness we made this summertime heartbreak bop for the AI (or maybe the AIM) era. Also my son said AutoTune is still in and he’s the coolest kid I know so go stream “Digital Girl,” in all its autotune glory everywhere! Link in bio.

MY FIRST FULL PRODUCTION! 
I remember making this beat in Las Vegas. It was really cold outside. 

I was trying to get that feeling from D’Angelo’s keys sound on Voodoo. Get that Boom Bap swing on the drums. That synth bass was fun to try and lock in. I tried not to quantize it so it felt more realistic and pocket. Guitar is all sampled and flipped from Splice. 

I immediately sent it to @jonathansingletary and was like, “what does this feel like to you” and he sent the joint back quick! Once he wrote it out, and he got the homie @enjoyjaredbrady to feature on that joint, BOOM, it was up and stuck. I usually co-produce on most records because I don’t have all the gadgets other producers have, so I’m proud of this one. Because it’s my first time putting out a record with an artist, that I did the full production on myself.

So add this to your “I’m grown” playlist, or whatever playlist gets you in “the mood”. 😇  link in bio!

Tonight Piano & Prayer is, as always, for those looking for solace. While much of the world is understandably captivated by fear, anger, and hopelessness, I offer up this small safe space to pray, to process, and to engage with God and yourself in order to heal.

While I have no interest in delivering  political statements as I recognize that social media cannot capture the fullness and complexities of anyone’s thoughts and feelings on this topic, I must acknowledge there is an inescapable political context to this painful time in our collective history.

I pray for a cease-fire, I pray for the safe return of hostages, and I pray for an end to a severely lopsided humanitarian crisis that could lead to the extermination of an innocent people in their own land. 

Sending love to all who are suffering in this painful season and I hope this space can contribute to your healing. I’ll be here playing piano and praying with anyone who needs it tonight at 5:30pm pst.
Thank you for joining Piano & Prayer today. Praying for this world 🙏🏾. Be blessed y’all.

Piano & Prayer has always been for those seeking a moment of peace and a space to heal and process. There is an atmosphere of grief, anger, fear, and tragedy that many are feeling and I don’t believe we can productively process any of it without God, breath, gratitude, prayer, and an earnest pursuit of guidance from our creator. Hopefully this hour can bring some balance to your journey to inform and empower your response. Praying we can also reconnect with what it means to be a vessel of love in these times.
